[5] Control, prevention, vaccine, research

Control
----------
4 Aug 2015 Sierra Leone: Expanding and accelerating response to calls for ambulances and burial teams for Sierra Leone's Ebola outbreak
http://www.cdc.gov/globalhealth/stories/ebola_call_center.html
[Thanks to the support of the CDC, the CDC Foundation, and eHealth Africa, at the 1-1-7 Ebola Call Center in Freetown, over 100 operators are working in 3 shifts to answer questions about Sierra Leone's outbreak 24 hours a day, 7 days a week. They work at a steady pace, on up-to-date software systems, answering callers' questions and entering requests for ambulances to pick up people with Ebola symptoms. They also log requests for burial teams to come to homes where they remove the bodies of the people who died to be tested for Ebola and receive safe and dignified burials... - more]

6 Aug 2015 Sierra Leone: Ebola head says country has 4 cases
http://medicalxpress.com/news/2015-08-sierra-leone-ebola-country-cases.html
[According to National Emergency Response Center [NERC] chief Alfred Palo Conteh, 2 of the cases tested negative after treatment and the other 2, in the north Tonkolili district, are in treatment. Conteh said the Tonkolili district remains a worry.

Authorities last week quarantined 500 people after a man died from Ebola. The district had not had a single case of Ebola in 5 months. The victim contracted the disease in the capital, traveled to his home village, and was treated for a fever at the local hospital but authorities didn't call the Ebola emergency number. "This could happen again in any of the silent districts and we must all do what it takes to prevent a recurrence elsewhere," Conteh said...more

The World Health Organization [WHO] on Wednesday [5 Aug 2015] said nearly 2000 contacts are being monitored in Guinea and Sierra Leone. WHO also warned that the rainy season in the 3 countries hit hardest by the Ebola outbreak -- Sierra Leone, Guinea and Liberia -- will prove a challenge for slowing the spread of the Ebola virus disease... - more]

8 Aug 2015 Sierra Leone: eases restrictions as Ebola danger recedes
http://www.ndtv.com/world-news/sierra-leone-eases-restrictions-as-ebola-danger-recedes-1205243
[Sierra Leoneans can go to sporting events and nightclubs for the 1st time in more than a year, after health officials declared there had been progress in rolling back a deadly epidemic of Ebola.]

5 Aug 2015 UN: Interagency collaboration on Ebola -- Situation Report
https://ebolaresponse.un.org/sites/default/files/icebola-sitrep_05august2015_0.pd
[This is the 1st situation report from the Interagency Collaboration on Ebola, and replaces situation reports previously produced by UNMEER (UN Mission for Ebola Emergency Response).]

8 Jul 2015 USA (California): Carlsbad ophthalmologist discusses the implications of a New England Journal of Medicine study linking uveitis and recovering Ebola virus patients
http://www.prweb.com/releases/2015/08/prweb12893267.htm
[According to Dr. Michael Tracy, the incidence of uveitis in some patients recovering from the Ebola virus, such as American physician Dr. Ian Crozier, did not present a threat of infection to the general public. "It is also important to stress that uveitis is an ocular condition that can affect many people for a variety of reasons, and developing the condition does not mean a patient is suffering from Ebola infection..." said Dr. Tracy...more]

Prevention
---------
7 Aug 2015 Ghana: forms Ebola response team to tackle any outbreak
http://gbcghana.com/1.5840202
[A national and zonal rapid response case management team has been formed in Accra as part of measures to tackle any Ebola outbreak. The team has stakeholders from both private and public health sectors as well as allied institutions at the regional and national levels to manage any Ebola outbreak. The Director, Institutional Care Division of the Ghana Health Service, Dr. Samuel Kaba, said the mandate of the team is to ensure that the country is mobilised in case of any Ebola emergency.]

6 Aug 2015 Nigeria: Ebola - council wants Nigerians to report unusual deaths of animals
http://allafrica.com/stories/201508061364.html
[The Veterinary Council of Nigeria (VCN) has called on Nigerians to be quick in alerting veterinary authorities about the unusual death of animals, especially non-primates around their home environments and farms ...more]

7 Aug 2015 Zambia: Inonge launches anti-Ebola plan
https://www.daily-mail.co.zm/?p=39300
[Vice-President Inonge Wina yesterday [6 Aug 2015] launched the Zambia Ebola preparedness and response plan for 2015, which will require over K 129 million [USD 24 200] to implement. The objective of the plan is to enhance a timely, consistent and coordinated response in case of any Ebola outbreak in the country.]

Vaccine
-----
3 Aug 2015 Canada: VSV-EBOV vaccine protects monkeys against Ebola when administered 7 days ahead
http://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2015-08/aaft-vpa080315.php
[This does not necessarily mean it will do the same for humans. - Mod.JW]

Research
-----
7 Aug 2015 USA: College students still largely misinformed about Ebola
http://uk.reuters.com/article/2015/08/07/us-health-ebola-university-idUKKCN0QC1MG20150807
[While 80 percent knew that Ebola is transmitted through body fluids, 31 percent believed incorrectly that it can be transmitted by mosquitoes, and 25 percent thought it could be spread by asymptomatic people in an airplane.]

